'''Robert Fulton Boyd''' (1858-1912) was an American [[physician]] and [[dentist]] who was the first president of the [[National Medical Association]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|title = The Journal of the National Medical Association: A Voice for Civil Rights and Social Justice|journal = American Journal of Public Health|date = 2010-04-01|issn = 0090-0036|pmc = 2837443|pmid = 20147673|pages = S70-S71|volume = 100|issue = Suppl 1|doi = 10.2105/AJPH.2009.175042|first = Sheena M.|last = Morrison|first2 = Elizabeth|last2 = Fee}}</ref> Boyd and other African-American physicians started the National Medical Association because, during the [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow]] era, the southern medical societies, medical facilities, and medical schools were [[Racial segregation|racially segregated]] by state laws.<ref name=":0" />

